events that followed within a bilateral framework. Game Changer broadens the canvas examining how America's desire to keep its two borders closed to threats but open to trade has influenced Canada and Mexico. The contributors draw on international relations theory to examine and explain not only how post-911 security policy has transformed relations between the three countries but also how policy makers can reconcile the need for greater regional cooperation in the security realm with national autonomy in other areas of life. By adopting a truly North American, or trilateral, framework, this challenging and authoritative volume suggests new approaches to security in the post-9/11 world.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 06. Mrz 2024) 0aNational securityzNorth America. 0aSeptember 11 Terrorist Attacks, 2001xInfluence. 7aPOLITICAL SCIENCE / Security (National & International).2bisacsh1 aAbelson, Donald E., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aBélanger, Louis, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aCimon, Yan, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aClarkson, Stephen, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aDoran, Charles F., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aHaglund, David G., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aHarvey, Frank P., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aHristoulas, Athanasios, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aJames, Patrick, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aJames, Patrick, eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/edt1 aLagassé, Philippe, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aMassie, Justin, econ